<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Mirror Image: Mr. Hyde Sees Mr. Hyde
</HL>
<DATE>
04/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A15
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<LP>
   According to your April 19 Asides, Czech public prosecutor
Tomas Sokol is threatening to outlaw the Czechoslovak
Communist Party under an existing statute prohibiting fascism
in that country.
   Should Mr. Sokol need expert testimony corroborating his
conclusion that communism and fascism are mirror-image
tyrannies, here are some testimonials from experts on the
subject:
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Susan Sontag (American liberal-intellectual author and
literary critic): "Not only is fascism (and overt military
rule) the probable destiny of all Communist societies --
especially when their populations are moved to revolt -- but
Communism is itself a variant, the most successful variant,
of fascism."
   Adolf Hitler: "The petit bourgeois Social Democrat and
trade union boss will never make a National Socialist, but
the Communist always will. . . . There is more that unites us
than divides us from Bolshevism . . . above all the genuine
revolutionary spirit."
   Andrei Sakharov (Russian dissident and Nobel Peace Prize
winner, to Soviet officials at the 1978 trial of Anatoly
Shcharansky): "You are not humans. You are fascists. Hear me,
a member of the Academy of Sciences. You are fascists."
   Seweryn Bailer (Columbia University professor of Russian
Studies and emigre from Poland): "I came to realize that the
system there {in the U.S.S.R.} involved all of the things I
had fought against in Nazism. And I made my decision on this
to leave that system at the first opportunity."
   Bernard-Henri Levy (French intellectual of the "New
Philosophers" Movement): "I am the bastard child of an unholy
union between fascism and Stalinism. . . . The only
revolution I know, the one which may grant notoriety to this
century, is the Nazi plague and Red fascism."
   Prof. A. James Gregor (author of "The Fascist Persuasion
in Radical Politics," Princeton University Press, 1974): ". .
. Fascist and Communist regimes are subspecies of one and the
same species. . . . In substance, whatever distinctions there
are between `fascist' and `communist' movements in terms of
ideological commitments -- they are singularly superficial."
   Although your Asides did not address the problem of
"former" Communist parties now calling themselves "Democratic
Socialist" or "Social Democratic," there is an urgent need in
geopolitics for a label distinguishing such parties from
those of Western "social democrats" -- who are, in truth,
free-enterprise welfare-state democrats, rather than
state-ownership socialists of Marxist tendency.
   The new label is "communoid," which simply indicates that
the political party in question most assuredly was Communist
(i.e. left-wing fascist) and, in its socialist heart of
hearts, may still be.
   Jim Guirard Jr.
   Washington
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900425-0127
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900425-0127.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Thermo Instrument
   To Acquire Finnigan
   For Up to $120 Million
</HL>
<DATE>
04/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6
</SO>
<CO>
   THI FNNG TMO
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
INDUSTRIAL EQUIPMENT, MACHINE TOOLS (IND)
DOW JONES INTERVIEW (CEO)
</IN>
<LP>
   WALTHAM, Mass. -- Thermo Instrument Systems Inc. said it
agreed to acquire Finnigan Corp. for $20 a share or $110
million to $120 million.
   Finnigan, which Thermo called the world's largest maker of
mass spectrometers, has been unprofitable in the face of
competitive pricing pressures. In over-the-counter trading
yesterday, Finnigan surged $4.50 to $18.75. Thermo
Instrument, an 80%-owned subsidiary of Thermo Electron Corp.,
rose 12.5 cents to $14.375. Thermo Instrument makes
instruments for environmental testing.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In the first quarter, Finnigan, San Jose, Calif., had a
net loss of $1.1 million, or 20 cents a share, on sales of
$30.3 million.
   Arvin Smith, president of Thermo Instrument, said that for
the first quarter his company expects to report net income
rose almost 30% to about $4.1 million, or 17 cents a share,
from a restated $3.2 million or 16 cents a share. The number
of shares outstanding increased to 24 million from a restated
19.7 million to reflect the conversion of debentures. Sales
rose 19% to about $49 million from a restated $41.2 million,
he said.
   The Finnigan acquisition would be Thermo Instrument's
second consecutive purchase of a struggling company. In
January, Thermo Instrument completed the stock acquisition of
Thermo Environmental Corp., another Thermo Electron
affiliate.
   Thermo Instrument's main business is making instruments
used to test and monitor air, water and nuclear pollution
sources. That business has been growing strongly as
corporations increasingly worry about toughened pollution
regulations. Thermo Environmental, whose sales account for
about 30% of the combined company, runs laboratories that
conduct such tests.
   The Finnigan acquisition is subject to approval by each
board, execution of a definitive acquisition agreement, and
receipt of regulatory and other approvals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900425-0126
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900425-0126.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Dividend News:
   ADAC Laboratories
</HL>
<DATE>
04/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   ADAC
</CO>
<IN>
DIVIDENDS (DIV)
</IN>
<LP>
   ADAC LABORATORIES said it suspended its quarterly common
stock dividend because of a slowdown in orders from
customers. The Milpitas, Calif., medical imaging equipment
company last paid a four cent dividend in its fiscal second
quarter ended April 1. A spokesman for the company said Adac
has been affected by slower orders from hospitals, which the
company said are "taking a harder look at their capital
budgets." In addition, the company said it has been hurt by
increased competition. For the second quarter, the company
had net income of $1.2 million, or three cents a share, down
nearly 71% from the $4.1 million, or nine cents a share, a
year earlier. Revenue declined nearly 17% to $20 million from
$24 million.
</LP>
