<HL>
   GM Likely to Move
   Camaro and Firebird
   Production to Canada
   ----
   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup
</HL>
<DATE>
04/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   GM LABOR
</CO>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
</IN>
<LP>
   DETROIT -- General Motors Corp. is expected to announce
today that it will move production of its Chevrolet Camaro
and Pontiac Firebird muscle cars to a Canadian plant from one
in Southern California.
   But GM and United Auto Workers union officials said
yesterday there is still a chance that the 43-year-old Van
Nuys, Calif., factory that currently builds the cars will not
join the seven other GM assembly plants that have halted
production or been targeted for shutdown since 1988.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   GM scheduled a news conference at its Ste. Therese,
Quebec, plant for this afternoon. A GM spokesman in Canada
wouldn't elaborate on the reasons for the news conference.
Officials of the Canadian Auto Workers union said they're
expecting the official announcement that the Canadian factory
will build the next generation of the Camaro-Firebird,
beginning in 1992.
   The Ste. Therese plant, which currently builds a line of
midsized cars, recently got a new paint shop with the help of
220 million Canadian dollars (US$189.5 million) in
interest-free Canadian government financing. Union officials
there also have agreed to company demands for more flexible
work rules.
   GM and United Auto Workers union officials insisted
yesterday the Van Nuys plant may survive, despite its age,
its distance from GM's major parts operations and the poor
quality marks accorded its current products. Company and
union officials say they are working on plans to make the
plant into a flexible factory capable of building several
different models for the West Coast market.
   "We're very optimistic that we'll be able to convert Van
Nuys" into a flexible manufacturing plant, a GM spokeswoman
said yesterday. "We don't expect it to close," added Henry
Gonzalez, assistant director for the UAW region that covers
California.
   Moreover, by moving the Van Nuys plant's cars to Canada,
GM could trigger provisions of the current UAW-GM agreement
that prohibit layoffs except as a result of a sales downturn,
UAW officials said. Under those provisions, GM would have to
keep the 3,000 Van Nuys workers on the payroll even if they
had no production work to do.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900425-0119
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900425-0119.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Dividend News:
   Schering-Plough
   Sets 2-for-1 Split,
   Boosts Dividend
   ----
   By Robert Daniels
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C6
</SO>
<CO>
   SGP WLA
</CO>
<IN>
DIVIDENDS (DIV)
</IN>
<LP>
   Schering-Plough Corp. directors declared a 2-for-1 stock
split and lifted the quarterly dividend 24%, while Warner
Lambert Co. holders approved an increase in authorized shares
to effect a previously announced 2-for-1 split.
   At Schering, the moves reflect "several consecutive years
of outstanding earnings growth and good business
performance," said Robert P. Luciano, chairman and chief
executive officer of the Madison, N.J., pharmaceuticals
concern.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The split is payable May 30 to stock of record May 4. The
dividend increase, to 56 cents a share from 45 cents, is
payable May 21 to stock of record May 4. At March 31,
Schering had 113.3 million shares outstanding.
   Shareholders at Schering's annual meeting also rejected
two shareholder proposals: that the company stop doing
business in South Africa, and that it report annually to
holders on the scope of its use of animals in testing
products and on its efforts to stop using animals for
testing.
   Warner-Lambert reiterated a projection that earnings per
share will rise at least 16% in 1990, adjusted for the split.
In 1989, Warner-Lambert earned $6.10 a share.
   Shareholders at the annual meeting of the Morris Plains,
N.J., health-care and consumer products company approved a
doubling of authorized common, to 300 million shares.
Warner-Lambert will pay the split on or about May 16 to stock
of record May 2. Warner-Lambert has about 67 million shares
outstanding.
   Warner-Lambert holders also defeated shareholder proposals
that the company quit operating in South Africa and implement
cumulative voting for directors. Under cumulative voting,
each shareholder has a number of votes equal to the number of
shares he or she owns times the number of directors up for
election. A shareholder may allot the votes among the
director candidates in any way he or she wishes.
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday,
Schering shares rose 25 cents to $80.125, while
Warner-Lambert's fell $1 to $105.75.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
