</DOCID>
<HL>
   Florida to Begin Spraying
   For Fruit Fly Protection
</HL>
<DATE>
04/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<IN>
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
</IN>
<LP>
   OPA LOCKA, Fla. -- State agriculture officials said they
plan to begin spraying parts of south Florida to combat a
possible infestation of Mediterranean fruit flies.
   Officials said yesterday that they had discovered a fifth
Medfly in Dade County. The first fly was discovered about a
week ago. The flies are a potentially serious threat to the
state's extensive citrus crops.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The state plans to fight the flies in two ways: aerial
spraying of malathion and the release of millions of sterile
flies. The sterile flies mate with the wild Medflies to
produce non-fertile eggs.
   While discussing the sprayings, Doyle Conner, the state's
commissioner of agriculture, said, "In spite of the recent
adverse publicity in California, there is overwhelming
scientific evidence that aerial application of malathion
doesn't pose any significant public health concern."
   Officials said they will widely publicize dates and times
of the sprayings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900425-0107
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900425-0107.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Technology:
   Digital Equipment, Apple
   To Unveil Joint Products
</HL>
<DATE>
04/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   DEC AAPL
</CO>
<IN>
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
SOFTWARE (SOF)
</IN>
<LP>
   Digital Equipment Corp. and Apple Computer Inc. will
announce long-awaited products next week that tie their
computers together.
   The expected products are the first fruits of a widely
heralded technology alliance disclosed two years ago. Kenneth
H. Olsen, Digital's president, and Apple's chief executive
officer, John Sculley, will show off the products next
Tuesday in New York.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The software products permit Apple computers to operate
easily in Digital networks, sharing data files, printers and
other devices.
   The companies view the alliance as a strategic one, though
they concede it isn't likely to set off a flood of new sales.
Analysts say it should help Apple's prospects in commercial
and industrial accounts, where Apple has been slow to
penetrate, while shoring up Digital's appeal to desktop
computer users, where it historically has been weak. Digital,
based in Maynard, Mass., will market the products.
</TEXT>
