<HL>
   Orbital Sciences Launches
   Initial Public Offer at $14
</HL>
<DATE>
04/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   ORBI
</CO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
INITIAL STOCK OFFERINGS (INI)
</IN>
<LP>
   FAIRFAX, Va. -- After launching its experimental Pegasus
rocket, Orbital Sciences Corp. finally launched its initial
public offering.
   The company sold about 2.4 million shares at $14 each
Monday -- $1 a share more than the company had planned last
month when it abruptly canceled the offering. On the day of
the proposed offering, a Wall Street Journal article
appeared, describing the steep risks involved in the Pegasus
project and apparently spooking the company and investors.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But since that time, things have gone well for Orbital
Sciences. In early April, it successfully launched Pegasus,
which is carried on the wing of a B-52 bomber and is dropped
over the ocean before it ignites. Pegasus is designed to
carry small satellites into space -- an emerging market that
has largely been ignored by the big aerospace companies as
too risky or too small.
   Cash-strapped Orbital Sciences sold about 1,250,000 shares
itself, raising about $17.5 million, before underwriting
fees. Outside investors sold about 1,150,000 shares. Orbital
Sciences didn't return calls seeking comment. Its
underwriter, Alex. Brown &amp; Sons, confirmed that the shares
had been sold.
   Yesterday, in its first day of trading, the rocket
company's shares opened at $14.50 in over-the-counter trading
and closed at $14. About 1.2 million shares were traded.
</TEXT>
