<HL>
   Technology:
   EPA Considers Proposals
   To Recycle, Reduce CFCs
</HL>
<DATE>
04/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8
</SO>
<IN>
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)
</IN>
<GV>
ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY (EPA)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Environmental Protection Agency is
considering a range of recycling proposals designed to reduce
emissions of air conditioning coolants and other chemicals
that damage the stratospheric ozone layer.
   These chemicals -- chlorofluorocarbons, or CFCs -- are
frequently released when auto and commercial air conditioning
and refrigeration units are serviced. The EPA proposals,
which include mandatory and voluntary recycling programs, are
designed to ensure that the chemicals are reused, rather than
released into the atmosphere.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The ozone layer helps shield the Earth from harmful
ultraviolet radiation, which causes skin cancer.
   President Bush has committed the U.S. to phase out the
production and importation of CFCs by the year 2000, under an
international treaty process. An EPA official explained that
recycling could cut $2 billion from industry's estimated $4.7
billion cost of phasing out CFCs and halons, another
ozone-depleting chemical, by 2000.
   A notice inviting public comment on the proposals will
appear in the Federal Register soon.
   Initially, the program would focus on the motor-vehicle
air conditioning industry, which accounts for 21% of CFC use
in the U.S. The agency estimates that 63% of CFC use in the
U.S. occurs in industries where recycling is feasible.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900425-0056
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900425-0056.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International Brief -- Hoechst AG:
   German Chemical Company
   Raises Dividend to Holders
</HL>
<DATE>
04/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C12
</SO>
<CO>
   G.HFA G.BAY
</CO>
<IN>
DIVIDENDS (DIV)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Hoechst AG joined other major West German chemical
companies by boosting its annual cash dividend for 1989 to 13
Deutsche marks ($7.64) a share from the 12 marks a share paid
for the previous year.
   Earlier in the day, Bayer AG announced a similar dividend
boost to 13 marks a share, while the last of the big three
West German chemical groups, BASF AG, said last week it would
boost its regular cash payout by a mark to 13 marks and
distribute a special one-mark cash payout to holders to
celebrate the company's 125th anniversary.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Hoechst also said group net profit in 1989 rose 5.7% to
2.13 billion marks from 2.02 billion marks in 1988. Group
sales rose 12% to 45.9 billion marks from 40.96 billion
marks.
   Bayer's group after-tax profit last year rose 11% to 2.12
billion marks from 1.91 billion marks.
</TEXT>
