<HL>
   Business Brief -- Melville Corp.:
   First-Quarter Net Fell 68%
   Largely Due to Late Easter
</HL>
<DATE>
04/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   MES
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
SPECIALTY RETAILERS (OTS)
</IN>
<LP>
   Melville Corp., Rye, N.Y., said first-quarter earnings
plunged 68%, largely because the Easter selling period falls
in the second quarter this year.
   Melville, a specialty retailer of apparel, footwear,
prescription drugs and other businesses, said net income fell
to $7.8 million, or four cents a share, from $24.2 million,
or 22 cents a share, a year earlier. Sales rose 5.8% to $1.62
billion from $1.53 billion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Melville noted that the Palm Sunday and Easter week
selling periods occurred in the second quarter of 1990 but in
the first quarter of 1989.
   The company also noted that it issued preference stock
last June on which the quarterly dividend is $3.9 million;
the year earlier per-share figure didn't reflect a preference
stock dividend.
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading, Melville
fell 50 cents $45.25.
</TEXT>
