<HL>
   CD Yields Rose
   At Banks, Brokers
   In Latest Week
   ----
   By Ellen E. Schultz
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C16
</SO>
<IN>
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   Yields on certificates of deposit at major banks and
brokerage firms rose across the board -- pushing past the 9%
level for a five-year CD at one major bank.
   The increases in the week ended yesterday coincided with a
sharp rise in market interest rates that has pushed yields on
longer-term Treasury securities up to nearly 9%.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The biggest increases in CD yields were among
small-denomination CDs sold by leading brokerage firms. The
average yield on one-year broker-sold CDs rose to 8.50% from
8.19%, while the five-year-CD average rose to 8.85% from
8.57%, according to figures compiled by Banxquote Money
Markets, a New York information service.
   Average yields for most large-denomination CDs, which
typically require deposits of $90,000 or more, were also up
significantly. The greatest gains were in the longer-term
maturities. Average yields on two-year jumbo CDs were 8.43%,
while five-year maturities were 8.54%. In New York, Chase
Manhattan Bank raised the yield on its five-year CD to 9.17%,
one of the highest in the country.
   "Nine percent is a psychological resistance level," said
Banxquote Chairman Norberto Mehl. "Once one of the leading
banks has crossed this level, other banks are expected to
follow."
   Mr. Mehl said that some of the leading brokers, such as
Shearson Lehman Hutton and Dean Witter Reynolds, are also
offering CDs that are approaching the 9% level.
   Meanwhile, average yields on small-denomination CDs at 18
banks surveyed by Banxquote rose only slightly. The average
yield on a one-year consumer CD rose to 8.02% from 7.96%,
while five-year consumer CDs offered 8.20%, up from 8.16%.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900425-0005
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900425-0005.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Monsanto Profit Fell
   13% in First Quarter;
   Chemical Lines Cited
</HL>
<DATE>
04/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8
</SO>
<CO>
   MTC
</CO>
<IN>
CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   ST.LOUIS -- Monsanto Co. said first-quarter profit fell
13% from a year-ago, to $194 million, or $2.95 a share.
   The report had been expected since last month, when the
company said it expected lower corporate profit because of
profit declines in its core chemical businesses.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A year earlier, Monsanto earned $222 million, or $3.24 a
share. Sales in the latest quarter were $2.29 billion, up 1%,
from $2.27 billion a year ago.
   In the crop chemicals unit, pretax profit fell to $151
million, from the record $184 million of last year. The
company said many shipments of its Lasso herbicide were
delayed until the second quarter because of changes in
farmers' purchasing patterns. In addition, the company said,
the sales mix of its Roundup herbicides tilted toward the
lower-priced formulations during the latest quarter.
   Analysts have said that, because the timing of
crop-chemical purchases varies, results for the first six
months are a better indicator of how the business is doing
than are results for the first quarter. Richard Mahoney,
Monsanto's chairman and chief executive officer, said the
company still expects profit from the crop-chemicals business
in 1990 to exceed last year's, given "reasonable weather."
   In the other chief chemicals unit, whose products include
plastic for shatterproof windshields, pretax profit dropped
to $119 million, from $130 million. Monsanto attributed the
decline to lower production in the auto industry.
   The other profit decline within Monsanto came in its
NutraSweet Co. unit, which had pretax profit of $67 million,
down from a record $74 million a year ago. In the G.D. Searle
&amp; Co. unit, pretax profit was $4 million, against a loss of
$8 million a year ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900425-0004
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900425-0004.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Dow Chemical Profit
   Fell 38% in Quarter,
   Hurt by Lower Prices
</HL>
<DATE>
04/25/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8
</SO>
<CO>
   DOW
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)
</IN>
<LP>
   MIDLAND, Mich. -- Dow Chemical Co. said first-quarter
earnings dropped 38% with the combined effects of higher
feedstock costs and lower commodity prices.
   The chemical and specialty-product company said net income
fell to $462 million, or $1.71 a share, from $743 million, or
$2.72 a share, a year earlier.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Sales increased 9.3% to $4.9 billion from $4.49 billion.
   Results were slightly below the expected range of $1.75 to
$1.90 a share. But several analysts said they weren't
downgrading estimates for the year, which ranged from $6.25
to $7.40, depending on economic forecasts.
   The company said results were "good" and represented a
return to "more normal" earnings levels, following a record
high in the 1989 first quarter. Dow Chemical shares closed at
$61, down 50 cents, in New York Stock Exchange composite
trading yesterday.
   The company said sales volume increased 18%, but prices
fell nearly 8% and hydrocarbon and energy costs were up
nearly 6%. Operating profit dropped 43% for chemicals and
performance products, 42% for plastics and 89% for
hydrocarbons and energy. Negative effects of commodity
chemicals were partly offset by consumer, agriculture and
pharmaceutical products, where sales rose 62% and operating
profit doubled.
   "Clearly, our diversification strategy is paying off,"
said Frank Popoff, president and chief executive officer.
   Mr. Popoff said results for 1990 will be "strong," but
below 1989 net of $2.49 billion, or $9.20 a share. The
second-quarter outlook is improving with declining costs and
rising prices for several high-volume products, he says. But
analyst Theodore S. Semegran of Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
warned that rising petrochemical capacity through 1992 would
continue to shrink margins and hold down earnings this year
and in 1991.
</TEXT>
